      <exits n='732' ne='669' e='732' se='732' s='732' sw='732' w='731' nw='732'/>
   </location>

   <location num='772'>
      <name>Mars shuttle landing pad</name>
      <desc>   This is the shuttle landing area of Marsport, in the northwest corner of the spaceport. Personal shuttles are parked in bays, ready to transport their owners back to their orbiting ships. They all seem to have a reddish tinge to them - caused by the red dust that constantly blows around in the thin Martian atmosphere.</desc>
      <exits e='773' se='837' s='836' no-exit='moves.noexit.4'/>
   </location>

   <location num='773'>
      <name>Marsport</name>
      <desc>   This northeastern part of Marsport is unused at the moment - the spaceport was built to cater for far more traffic than it currently gets.</desc>
      <desc>   There is a road leading north, out of the spaceport, and in the distance you can see the buildings which make up the main city on Mars. South is an open area, while the general landing area is west.</desc>
      <desc>   A sign indicates that the special hopper that has been sponsored by Diesel, to take customers straight to her bar, has been replaced by a toboggan. Just wait a moment and one will be along, then you can get IN.</desc>
      <exits n='709' s='837' sw='836' w='772' in='579' no-exit='moves.noexit.4'/>
   </location>

   <location num='779'>
      <name>Beaten track</name>
      <desc>   You are standing at the end of a well-worn path which runs northwest into open country. To the east the track runs into a bizarre set of ruins, whose outlines seem to blur and merge even as you watch.</desc>
      <exits e='780' nw='714' in='780'/>
   </location>

   <location num='780'>
      <name>Before the Ruins</name>
      <desc>   Before you lie the ruins of an ancient Martian city. A huge archway leads east, into the ruins - it seems to twist and change shape even as you look at it.</desc>
      <desc>   Generations of archeologists have worked in these ruins, trying to understand what the Martians were like. They have done their best not to leave any trace of their work, and they are helped by some strange force that seems to keep the remains in a timeless state.</desc>
      <desc>   A narrow track leads away from the ruins and out to open country to the west.</desc>
      <exits e='781' w='779' in='781' out='779'/>
   </location>

   <location num='781' flags='t'>
      <name>Archway</name>
      <desc>   This must surely be the biggest archway you have ever seen. Underneath it, its shadow blocks out any light. Impossibly slender fluted arches support massive slabs, colors flicker along whorls etched into the sides.</desc>
      <desc>   Hanging over it all is an electric tension - and an absolute silence - as though the city is waiting for an event...</desc>
      <desc>   The bulk of the city crouches, like a beast of prey, to the east, while to the west lies open countryside.</desc>
      <exits e='782' w='780' in='782' out='780' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='782' flags='t'>
      <name>Alleyway</name>
      <desc>   This narrow winding alleyway leads from a huge archway in the west into the ruins to the east. There is a possibility that you could squeeze into one of the ruined buildings by going through a gap in a wall to your south.</desc>
      <exits e='783' s='846' w='781' in='846' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='783' flags='t'>
      <name>Alleyway</name>
      <desc>   You are in a winding east/west alley. There is an entrance to the southeast.</desc>
      <exits e='784' se='848' w='782' in='848' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='784' flags='t'>
      <name>Open space</name>
      <desc>   This is a perfectly circular open space. Alleyways run off it to the north and the west.</desc>
      <exits n='720' w='783' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='785' flags='t'>
      <name>Long room</name>
      <desc>   The room runs in an arc from the north to the southwest, and even here in the center you cannot see either of the ends. Light enters through a large hole in the roof, casting strange shadows on the walls.</desc>
      <exits n='721' sw='848' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='786' flags='t'>
      <name>Hazy mist</name>
      <desc>      This room is full of a hazy mist, making it impossible to see anything at all. The mist is brighter to the southwest and darker to the north.</desc>
      <exits n='722' sw='849' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='793' flags='t'>
      <name>Maze of Alleys</name>
      <desc>   You are in a maze of narrow alleyways, with no obvious exits.</desc>
      <exits n='729' ne='793' e='793' se='793' s='793' sw='793' w='793' nw='793'/>
   </location>

   <location num='795' flags='t'>
      <name>Maze of Alleys</name>
      <desc>   You are in a maze of narrow alleyways, with no obvious exits.</desc>
      <exits n='731' ne='795' e='795' se='795' s='795' sw='795' w='795' nw='795'/>
   </location>

   <location num='836'>
      <name>Marsport</name>
      <desc>   The southwest corner of the spaceport is reserved for craft belonging to members of the Martian City Council. Some of the vessels parked here are extremely fancy - clearly, there are perks to being on the planet&apos;s ruling body.</desc>
      <desc>   The landing area is north.</desc>
      <exits n='772' ne='773' e='837' no-exit='moves.noexit.4'/>
   </location>

   <location num='837'>
      <name>Marsport</name>
      <desc>   This is the southeastern corner of Mars&apos;s spaceport, a large open area used for maneuvering ships before assigning them to their designated berths.</desc>
      <desc>   You can see vehicle tracks leading south, out into the vast emptiness of the Martian desert.</desc>
      <exits n='773' s='901' w='836' nw='772' no-exit='moves.noexit.4'/>
   </location>

   <location num='840'>
      <name>Martian face</name>
      <desc>   As you get closer to the image of the face, you can see it clearly. It&apos;s astonishing! The large yellow circle, the black dots for eyes, and the curve for the mouth... yes, there&apos;s no doubt: someone has painted an enormous smiley face on the rock. You wonder if it is visible from orbit...</desc>
      <desc>   The trail leads south, back down the rock.</desc>
      <exits s='904' down='904' no-exit='moves.noexit.5'/>
   </location>

   <location num='846' flags='t'>
      <name>Red room</name>
      <desc>   This is part of a large room, which is decorated in various shades of red. The room continues to the east and the south, and there is a doorway to the north which lets in some light.</desc>
      <exits n='782' e='847' s='910' out='782' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='847' flags='t'>
      <name>Red room</name>
      <desc>   This is part of a large room which is decorated entirely in differing shades of red. The room continues to the west and the south.</desc>
      <exits s='911' w='846' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='848' flags='t'>
      <name>Long room</name>
      <desc>   This room curves around to the northeast, and you cannot see what is at the other end. There is a doorway in the northwestern wall.</desc>
      <exits ne='785' nw='783' out='783' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='849' flags='t'>
      <name>Lines room</name>
      <desc>   You are in a large room. All around are people dressed in archaic clothes. When you try to touch them, you discover that they have no substance.</desc>
      <desc>   The room is lit by brightly glowing lines and whorls which cover the walls from floor to ceiling. You shiver as though someone had walked over your grave...</desc>
      <desc>   The only visible openings are northeast, southeast and southwest.</desc>
      <exits ne='786' se='914' sw='912' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
      <events no-exit='death.lines.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='901'>
      <name>Desert</name>
      <desc>   The soil of the Martian desert is red, caused by rust in the soil. It&apos;s bone dry, and every step you take causes sand particles to fly up.</desc>
      <desc>   The passage of vehicles has worn a path through the otherwise featureless desert, travelling between the spaceport, to the north, and a large crater to the southeast.</desc>
      <exits n='837' se='966' no-exit='moves.noexit.5'/>
   </location>

   <location num='904'>
      <name>Rocky trail</name>
      <desc>   The trail leads up the side of a large rock. It&apos;s very steep, but the low Martian gravity makes it easy to climb.</desc>
      <desc>   As you reach the top of the rock, you look over it and see yet more big red rocks. The nearest one seems to have an image of some kind on the side. Surprisingly, it looks a bit like a face!</desc>
      <exits n='840' sw='967' down='967' no-exit='moves.noexit.5'/>
   </location>

   <location num='910' flags='t'>
      <name>Red room</name>
      <desc>   This is the southwest corner of the red room. At floor level there are several holes in the wall - too small for you to get through, but big enough for a large rodent.</desc>
      <exits n='846' e='911' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='911' flags='t'>
      <name>Red room</name>
      <desc>   This is the southeast corner of a large room decorated in varying shades of red. To your east is an opening in the wall. Through the opening you can see a swirling, milky mist.</desc>
      <exits n='847' e='912' w='910' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='912' flags='t'>
      <name>Hazy mist</name>
      <desc>   This room is full of a hazy mist. It is difficult to tell where the light is coming from, but the mist appears to be darker to the west and brighter to the northeast.</desc>
      <exits ne='849' w='911' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='914' flags='t'>
      <name>Slab room</name>
      <desc>   This is a very ancient and musty smelling room. In the center is a massive slab of iron. The iron must have been given special treatment, because there is no sign of rust, in spite of the moisture-laden atmosphere.</desc>
      <desc>   There are many remains (human and otherwise) strewn around the room, indicating that it must have once been deadly. Archeologists investigating the ruins have been examining the bones, and someone with a morbid sense of tidiness has laid out some skulls in a row on the slab.</desc>
      <desc>   There is only one exit - an opening to the northwest.</desc>
      <exits nw='849' out='849' no-exit='moves.noexit.1'/>
   </location>

   <location num='966'>
      <name>Desert</name>
      <desc>   The Martian desert is bleak and featureless. The wind whips up the red sand into a sandstorm, making it hard to see where you are going. Your nano-chameleon suit is going to have sand in all its little crevices.</desc>
      <desc>   The trail splits here; southeast, it continues towards a large crater, while a smaller path leads east, between some red rocks. The way back to civilization is northwest.</desc>
      <exits e='967' se='1031' nw='901' no-exit='moves.noexit.5'/>
   </location>

   <location num='967'>
      <name>Rocky trail</name>
      <desc>   The trail winds its way through rocks, which have been eroded over the years by stinging winds, until they form strange shapes and patterns. Northeast, the trail leads up a large rock; almost a hillside. West it joins the main trail.</desc>
      <exits ne='904' w='966' up='904' no-exit='moves.noexit.5'/>
   </location>

   <location num='1031'>
      <name>Crater edge</name>
      <desc>   The trail stops at the edge of a large crater. If you had paid more attention to Martian geography, you might know what the name of the crater was...</desc>
      <desc>   There&apos;s some kind of machinery dotted around on the floor of the crater. It looks as though you could just about clamber down to take a look.</desc>
      <exits se='1096' nw='966' down='1096' no-exit='moves.noexit.5'/>
   </location>

   <location num='1096'>
      <name>Probe graveyard</name>
      <desc>   This crater is used as a dumping ground for all the various spacecraft and probes that have been abandoned on the Martian surface over the centuries. The Martian town council decided to collect them all up and place them together - partly to get them out of the way, and partly as a memorial to past attempts at space exploration.</desc>
      <desc>   Around you have been placed the crumpled remains of some of the failures, which crash-landed and were never heard from again - until humans landed on the planet, and found the wreckage. Russian symbols on some of the remains are testament to the fact that the now defunct USSR was the first to attempt to reach the red planet.</desc>
      <desc>   The crater continues to the south, southeast and east. You can climb up, out of the crater, to the northwest.</desc>
      <exits e='1097' se='1161' s='1160' nw='1031' up='1031' no-exit='moves.noexit.7'/>
   </location>

   <location num='1097'>
      <name>Probe graveyard</name>
      <desc>   The remains of Viking I, the first successful Earth visitor to Mars, has been placed here. Although the surface of the craft has been scoured by sandstorms, it is still identifiable as the means by which Earth scientists first gathered information about the planet Mars.</desc>
      <desc>   The crater continues west, southwest and south.</desc>
      <exits s='1161' sw='1160' w='1096' no-exit='moves.noexit.7'/>
   </location>

   <location num='1160'>
      <name>Probe graveyard</name>
      <desc>   This part of the crater is taken up with probes from the late twentieth century. The Mars Pathfinder, and its rover Sojourner, are displayed prominently. The lander has lost most of its solar panels, but the Sojourner looks as if just a little bit of work would get it running again.</desc>
      <desc>   There are also some memories of embarrassing failures, with various craft that crashed, or that landed safely but failed to do anything after that. A plaque on the Mars Climate Orbiter reminds you that it crashed because of the confusion between Imperial and Metric units. Nearby is the peculiar unfolding contraption that makes up Beagle 2, lost without trace after landing, and its equally unsuccessful successors, Beagles 3, 4 and 5, as well as the successful Beagle 6, which was the first probe to confirm that life had once existed on Mars.</desc>
      <desc>   The crater continues north, northeast and east.</desc>
      <exits n='1096' ne='1097' e='1161' no-exit='moves.noexit.7'/>
   </location>

   <location num='1161'>
      <name>Probe graveyard</name>
      <desc>   This part of the crater contains the remains of the first manned ship to land on Mars: the Minerva 2. Although the ship landed safely, and the crew were able to explore and send back information, after a few days every one of them vanished without trace, and even to this day nobody knows what happened to those brave men and women.</desc>
      <desc>   Next to it is the Minerva 3.1, the first completely successful Mars landing. Crew from the Minerva 3.1 built the first buildings of what is now Marsport, and became the very first colonists.</desc>
      <desc>   The crater continues to the north, northwest and west.</desc>
      <exits n='1097' w='1160' nw='1096' no-exit='moves.noexit.7'/>
   </location>

</fed2-map>
